@DATABASE "pgmtopbm.guide"
@INDEX "ImageEditor.guide/INDEX"
@FONT helvetica.font 13
@SMARTWRAP

@NODE MAIN "ImageEditor - Converter: GreyToBitmap [pgmtopbm]"
@TOC "Converter.guide/MAIN"

@{LINDENT 4}
@{PAR}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{B}GreyToBitmap@{UB}@{FG TEXT}@{LINE}
@{PAR}@{B}Convert a portable graymap into a portable bitmap.@{UB}@{LINE}
@{PAR}Reads a portable graymap as input. Produces a portable bitmap as output.@{LINE}
@{PAR}The default quantization method is boustrophedonic Floyd-Steinberg error diffusion.
Also available are simple thresholding; Bayer's ordered dither with a 16x16 matrix;
and three different sizes of 45-degree clustered-dot dither.
A space filling curve halftoning method using the Hilbert curve is also available.@{LINE}
@{PAR}Floyd-Steinberg will almost always give the best looking results; however, looking good is not always what you want.
For instance, clustered-dot dithering gives a newspaper-ish look, a useful special effect.@{LINE}
@{PAR}The Hilbert curve method is useful for processing images before display on devices that do not render individual pixels distinctly (like laser printers).
This dithering method can give better results than the dithering usually done by the laser printers themselves.
Typically a PGM image will have to be scaled to fit on a laser printer page (2400 x 3000 pixels for an A4 300 dpi page),
and then dithered to a PBM image before being converted to a postscript file.@{LINE}
@{PAR}See also @{" BitmapToGrey " LINK "pbmtopgm.guide/MAIN"}.@{LINE}
